An exhaustive compendium of judicial pronouncements, this article delves into the cases chronicled within [volume 307](/United_States_Reports) of [United States Reports](/United_States_Reports), encapsulating decisions rendered by the highest judicial authority in the land, the [Supreme Court of the United States](/Supreme_Court_of_the_United_States), throughout the year 1939. One might find it a rather dry chronicle of humanity's endless squabbles, but even these dusty tomes hold the echoes of seismic shifts in the legal landscape.

### The Supreme Court of the United States: A Brief, Weary Overview

Located in the rather grand, if somewhat imposing, structure at 38°53′26″N 77°00′16″W in [Washington, D.C.](/Washington,_D.C.), the [Supreme Court of the United States](/Supreme_Court_of_the_United_States) stands as the apex of the federal judiciary. Its very existence, established on March 4, 1789—a mere 236 years ago, which in the grand scheme of things, is barely a blink—was a foundational act in the nascent republic's assertion of ordered liberty. The Court's creation is rooted in [Article III, Section 1](/Article_Three_of_the_United_States_Constitution) of the [Constitution of the United States](/Constitution_of_the_United_States), which declares with stark simplicity that "The judicial Power of the United States, shall be vested in one supreme Court..." This seemingly straightforward directive established a singular, ultimate arbiter of legal disputes, a concept both elegant and, as history has shown, fraught with human interpretation.

The appointment process for these purveyors of justice involves a presidential nomination followed by the Senate's often contentious [confirmation](/Advice_and_consent). Once seated, a justice enjoys a tenure that is, quite remarkably, for life, or until retirement, resignation, or the rather more dramatic event of [impeachment](/Federal_impeachment_in_the_United_States) and removal. Currently, and by long-standing statute, the Court comprises nine positions: one [Chief Justice](/Chief_Justice_of_the_United_States) and eight [Associate Justices](/Associate_Justice_of_the_Supreme_Court_of_the_United_States). Their official digital presence can be found at supremecourt.gov, for those who wish to delve into the labyrinthine details directly.

This article, much like a minor cog in a vast, indifferent machine, forms but a small part of a larger series dedicated to the intricate workings of the [Supreme Court of the United States](/Supreme_Court_of_the_United_States). Within this broader framework, one might explore the Court's storied [History](/History_of_the_Supreme_Court_of_the_United_States), the enigmatic [Procedures](/Procedures_of_the_Supreme_Court_of_the_United_States) governing its daily machinations, the often-politicized process of [Nomination and confirmation](/Nomination_and_confirmation_to_the_Supreme_Court_of_the_United_States), the granular scrutiny of [Judiciary Committee review](/Senate_Judiciary_Committee_reviews_of_nominations_to_the_Supreme_Court_of_the_United_States), the fascinating statistical breakdowns of its [Demographics](/Demographics_of_the_Supreme_Court_of_the_United_States) and the ever-shifting sands of the [Ideological leanings of justices](/Ideological_leanings_of_United_States_Supreme_Court_justices). For the truly dedicated, there are also extensive [Lists of decisions](/Lists_of_United_States_Supreme_Court_cases) and details about the very edifice that houses this power, the [Supreme Court building](/United_States_Supreme_Court_Building).

