### Justices of the Supreme Court at the Time of Volume 307 U.S.

For context, the composition of the [Supreme Court](/List_of_justices_of_the_Supreme_Court_of_the_United_States) during the period when the cases in volume 307 of [United States Reports](/United_States_Reports) were decided is crucial. One can explore comprehensive details about all justices through the [List of justices of the Supreme Court of the United States](/List_of_justices_of_the_Supreme_Court_of_the_United_States), or perhaps delve into the specifics of their time on the bench via the [List of United States Supreme Court justices by time in office](/List_of_United_States_Supreme_Court_justices_by_time_in_office), or even examine the Court's historical configurations through the [List of justices of the Supreme Court of the United States by court composition](/List_of_justices_of_the_Supreme_Court_of_the_United_States_by_court_composition).

The very foundation of the Supreme Court, as previously noted, lies within [Article III, Section 1](/Article_Three_of_the_United_States_Constitution) of the [Constitution of the United States](/Constitution_of_the_United_States), which unequivocally states: "The judicial Power of the United States, shall be vested in one supreme Court . . .". What the Constitution notably omits, however, is the precise number of justices who should comprise this "one supreme Court," leaving that rather significant detail to the discretion of [Congress](/Congress_of_the_United_States). Historically, Congress has exercised this power with a certain degree of fluidity. The seminal [Judiciary Act of 1789](/Judiciary_Act_of_1789) initially fixed the number of justices at a modest six, consisting of one chief justice and five associate justices. Since that foundational act in 1789, Congress has shown a willingness to adjust the Court's size, expanding it to [seven](/Seventh_Circuit_Act_of_1807), then to [nine](/Eighth_and_Ninth_Circuits_Act_of_1837), briefly to [ten](/Tenth_Circuit_Act_of_1863), before settling back to the familiar [nine](/Judiciary_Act_of_1869) justices—a composition that has, for the most part, endured. This has always included a single chief justice, the guiding hand, or perhaps just the designated tie-breaker.

